 fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/CTA N/EDC N/EDI N/EEC N/GEN N/GENI N/IEN N/IMF N/PBP N/PLT N/TAX R/EC R/EU R/GE R/WEU </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday BERLIN CDU CSU INVESTMENT SDP TAX RELIEF TRADE TRUMP SB119038352400065136594045841153912045803881 Merkel, Angela Navarro, Peter Scholz, Olaf SYND CODES_REVIEWED Review &amp; Outlook (U.S.) </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">Opinion</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Germany's Sad Tax Truth; Germans suffer more than anyone from their fiscal surplus.</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>The message from Germany's new finance minister in his first interview with foreign press since taking office this month is that the punishment will continue for the foreseeable future. Olaf Scholz plans to resist tax cuts despite Berlin's ballooning fiscal surplus, he told The Wall Street Journal this week.</Para><Para>Mr. Scholz, a member of the center-left Social Democratic Party (SPD), said reform of the personal income tax will have to wait until after the next election in 2021. Corporate tax cuts, meanwhile, "are currently not on the agenda." That leaves Germans to make do with the paltry â‚¬10 billion in tax relief currently scheduled to kick in over the next four years, while Berlin's fiscal surplus expands to an expected 1.4% of GDP this year.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>Most commentators will view Mr. Scholz's comments as another move in Berlin's global game of trade-politics chess. Foreign critics such as the Trump Administration's court jester on trade policy, Peter Navarro, and the International Monetary Fund have long complained that Berlin's fiscal surpluses distort its trade and economy.</Para><Para>These wags keep demanding a Keynesian blow-out on public works to boost domestic German consumption. Chancellor Angela Merkel and her center-right Christian Democrats (CDU/CSU) are resisting those demands, and just as well. Germany's quality of roads, bridges, tunnels and the like is roughly equivalent to peers such as France and the U.S. Germany might need more investment, but that should happen among non-exporting companies in the private economy instead of via wasteful government projects. So it's a shame that corporate tax reform to stimulate investment is off the table.</Para><Para>Germany should be saving more than it spends and exporting more than it consumes given that its population is declining and its Baby Boomers will soon retire. But that doesn't mean the government should do the "saving" via an accumulation of fiscal surpluses. Far better to return money to overtaxed citizens who could find their own preferred mix of spending versus investment.</Para><Para>The German people are the biggest victims of Berlin's fiscal surpluses. The tax system imposes frighteningly steep marginal rates on lower-to-middle-income earners. Social taxes and the consumption tax add another layer of misery that hits lower-income taxpayers particularly hard. The voters missed an opportunity to demand tax relief in the last election, and now Mr. Scholz is effectively telling them better luck next time.</Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By The Editorial Board </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" 